Kenya has recorded 20 new cases of Covid-19 from a sample of 2,008 in the last 24 hours, representing a positivity rate of 1.0 per cent. According to the statement released on Monday, 14 are Kenyans while 6 are foreigners. Of these, 11 are males and nine are females. The youngest patient is a 13-year-old while the oldest is 71-years-old. The total number of confirmed positive cases is 324,046 out of a cumulative 3,635,279. In terms of county distribution: Nairobi 13, Mandera 4, Kiambu 2, Uasin Gishu 1. No patients have recovered from the disease. There were no deaths recorded. The cumulative number of deaths remain at 5,649. This brings the total number of recoveries remain 318,170 of whom 265,140 are from the HomeBased Care and Isolation program, while 53,030 are from various health facilities countrywide. Two patients are currently admitted to various health facilities countrywide, while 225 are under the Home-Based Isolation and Care program. No patients are on supplemental oxygen, the intensive care unit (ICU), or in the High Dependency Unit (HDU). Vaccination campaign As of May 16, a total of 18,008,306 vaccines had been administered across the country. Of these, 16,355,436 doses were administered to the adult population. Another 1,307,711 were administered to those between 15 to 17 years, 32,481 while 312,678 are booster doses. The total number of vaccines administered in the last 24 hours is 1,632 while the total number of people fully vaccinated in the same period was 750. The proportion of adults fully vaccinated was 30.7 per cent.